         <abstract>
            <p>An aliquot sequence $n : k, k = 0, 1, 2,\ldots$, is defined by $n: 0 = n, n: k + 1 = \sigma(n : k) - n : k$, and a driver of an aliquot sequence is a number $2^A \upsilon$ with $A &gt; 0, \upsilon \operatorname{odd}, \upsilon \mid 2^{A+1} - 1$ and $2^{A-1}\mid \sigma(\upsilon)$. Pollard has noted some errors in a proof in [1] that the drivers comprise the even perfect numbers and a finite set. These are now corrected in a revised proof.</p>
          </abstract>
